“The Kinetic Echo Loom – a haptic feedback device designed to translate the movements of a skilled artisan into a dynamically shifting, immersive haptic simulation. Worn as a full-body suit, the device utilizes advanced bio-sensors to capture and replicate the subtle muscle movements, joint angles, and force patterns of a craftsperson’s actions. These patterns are then translated into precisely calibrated vibrations, pressure waves, and temperature fluctuations across the suit’s surface, creating a visceral representation of the craft. Imagine learning to weave – not just watching a video, but *feeling* the shuttle’s pull, the threads’ resistance, the rhythmic motion of the loom, all translated into a captivating, multi-sensory experience. We can even integrate scent profiles—the smell of wood shavings, beeswax, or dye—to truly immerse the user. The device connects wirelessly to a ‘Master Archive’ – a database of movement patterns collected from renowned artisans around the world. Users can select a craft, a master, and begin their learning journey, feeling the movements of a master craftsman directly on their skin! I’m thinking of adding a ‘Retro-Fit’ mode – the ability to analyze your own movements and learn to emulate a master craftsperson.”